 MBOMBELA – After the overwhelming response following Morné Green’s 45-kilometre run on his 13-metre balcony, he decided to use this publicity to challenge the community for a good cause.  Green, a 36-year-old Mbombela resident, initially had one goal in mind – to beat marathon enthusiast Elisha Nochomovitz from France. “I have, however, decided to use this opportunity to get the community involved and help those in need, especially during these trying times,” he said. Green calls this project the Community Can Challenge. Also read: Community warned about possible escaped lion around Malalane “When you decide to replenish your household goods, consider buying a can of food for the less fortunate,” he said. Green aims to collect 49 902 cans of food – the same amount of steps he covered during his run.  Here’s how For now, collection bins are available at Crossing and The Grove SUPERSPARs. “If you wish to do so, take a picture and upload it to the Community Can Challenge Facebook page,” he said, and added that at a later stage, the cans will be distributed to the less fortunate local communities. Cash donations can be deposited into Penreach‘s bank account.  * Notice: Coronavirus reporting at Caxton Local Media aims to combat fake news Dear reader, As your local news provider, we have the duty of keeping you factually informed on Covid-19 developments. As you may have noticed, mis- and disinformation (also known as “fake news”) is circulating online. Caxton Local Media is determined to filter through the masses of information doing the rounds and to separate truth from untruth in order to keep you adequately informed. Local newsrooms follow a strict pre-publication fact-checking protocol. A national task team has been established to assist in bringing you credible news reports on Covid-19. Readers with any comments or queries may contact National Group Editor Irma Green (irma@caxton.co.za) or Legal Adviser Helene Eloff (helene@caxton.co.za).      